One possibility would be to generate the map of all properties on demand. Jackson can convert any Kotlin object to a Map like this:

```
val map = mapper.convertValue&lt;Map&lt;String, Any?&gt;&gt;(myKotlinObject)
```

For that to work, you&#39;d need to annotate your `dynamicFields` property with `@JsonAnyGetter` as well as `@JsonAnySetter`.

Here&#39;s a complete example:

```
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.*
import com.fasterxml.jackson.module.kotlin.*

data class Student(val name: String) {
    @JsonAnySetter
    @JsonAnyGetter
    private val dynamicFields: MutableMap&lt;String, Any?&gt; = mutableMapOf()
}

val mapper = jsonMapper { addModule(kotlinModule()) }

fun main() {
    val student = mapper.readValue&lt;Student&gt;(
        &quot;&quot;&quot;{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Alice&quot;, &quot;surname&quot;:&quot;Smith&quot;}&quot;&quot;&quot;
    )
    val allProperties = mapper.convertValue&lt;Map&lt;String, Any?&gt;&gt;(student)
    println(allProperties)
}

```

----

Alternatively, you could use [delegated properties and store all properties in a map](https://kotlinlang.org/docs/delegated-properties.html#storing-properties-in-a-map). There are some tradeoffs, since you lose the ability to set the properties in via the constructor. Here&#39;s what that might look like:

```
data class Student(
    @JsonAnySetter
    @JsonAnyGetter
    internal val map: MutableMap&lt;String, Any?&gt; = mutableMapOf()
) {
    val name: String by map

    override fun toString(): String {
        return &quot;Student(name=&#39;$name&#39;, dynamicFields=$map)&quot;
    }
}

val mapper = jsonMapper { addModule(kotlinModule()) }

fun main() {
    val student = mapper.readValue&lt;Student&gt;(
        &quot;&quot;&quot;{&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Alice&quot;, &quot;surname&quot;:&quot;Smith&quot;}&quot;&quot;&quot;
    )
    println(student.map)
    println(student.name)
}
```

Another drawback to that approach is that Jackson won&#39;t complain if required properties are missing; you won&#39;t find out until you try to access the property and get a `NoSuchElementException`.

